WEBVTT

NOTE
Draft captions matching the conversational narration in demo-script.md /
demo-transcript.md (and the read-off FINAL-SCRIPT.md). Cue times follow the
script's timing budget (target ~7:35). Before acceptance, reconcile them against
what is actually said on the recording; captions never override the real
narration. Synthetic MVP — no customer data.

1
00:00.000 --> 00:04.000
Synthetic MVP — no customer data.

2
00:04.000 --> 00:12.000
Hey — I'm Varun. I built this thing called
Mahoraga, let me walk you through it.

3
00:12.000 --> 00:20.000
Short version: it's a memory engine
for offensive security.

4
00:20.000 --> 00:28.000
One small service — Java, Postgres,
a real transactional ingestion path —

5
00:28.000 --> 00:35.000
plus deterministic synthetic fixtures. No LLM,
so it comes out identical every run.

6
00:35.000 --> 00:43.000
First — and I'll keep saying this —
everything here is fake data.

7
00:43.000 --> 00:51.000
A swarm attacks a customer, finds a bunch
of stuff, writes it down...

8
00:51.000 --> 00:58.000
then the engagement ends
and it throws the notebook away.

9
00:58.000 --> 01:05.000
Next quarter it starts from zero.
That's what I'm fixing — the memory.

10
01:05.000 --> 01:12.000
That preflight was just me being careful —
it changes nothing.

11
01:12.000 --> 01:22.000
This next command is the whole trick. Think of it
as standing in for the swarm —

12
01:22.000 --> 01:31.000
the thing that would normally run the attacks.

13
01:31.000 --> 01:41.000
Real engagements are messy, so I froze it into
a fixture: fixed checks, fixed results.

14
01:41.000 --> 01:50.000
On purpose — so the only thing that changes
between runs is Mahoraga's memory.

15
01:50.000 --> 01:56.000
It runs the whole second engagement twice —
memory off, then memory on.

16
01:56.000 --> 02:00.000
Same clean starting point.
A controlled experiment.

17
02:00.000 --> 02:10.000
See these three — T-A, T-B, T-C? Just three
checks the swarm could run next.

18
02:10.000 --> 02:20.000
To the planner they're totally opaque —
three IDs, no idea what they'll find.

19
02:20.000 --> 02:30.000
So its only job is: what order
do we run them in?

20
02:30.000 --> 02:40.000
Memory off, nothing to go on —
it runs them in order: A, B, C.

21
02:40.000 --> 02:52.000
Memory on, it sees one points at something
we'd already confirmed fixed —

22
02:52.000 --> 03:02.000
and a fix coming back is what you check first.
So it pulls it up: C, A, B.

23
03:02.000 --> 03:12.000
Both plans run, same frozen results. The bug that
came back? Memory catches it first, not third.

24
03:12.000 --> 03:20.000
Three to one. Same state, same outcomes —
the only difference was seeing history.

25
03:20.000 --> 03:29.000
The pod got a new ID, a new name, a new IP —

26
03:29.000 --> 03:37.000
everything you'd key on changed. But the
Deployment underneath is the same.

27
03:37.000 --> 03:45.000
So the finding stays stuck to it —
that's tracking a bug over time.

28
03:45.000 --> 03:55.000
And that's the point: it holds across
engagements even as name and IP churn.

29
03:55.000 --> 04:03.000
In real Kubernetes that's constant —
pods rescheduled, IPs recycled, names churn.

30
04:03.000 --> 04:09.000
The Deployment is what's stable,
so that's what we key on.

31
04:09.000 --> 04:15.000
Something fuzzy? It says "I don't know,"
marks it ambiguous, and moves no numbers.

32
04:15.000 --> 04:24.000
This is the one I'd show a customer.
Same exact Engagement 2 facts —

33
04:24.000 --> 04:33.000
I'm just changing how much history
it's allowed to look at.

34
04:33.000 --> 04:43.000
No memory, a normal scan: three detections,
one not-detected, one partial.

35
04:43.000 --> 04:53.000
And the finding nobody retested? It just isn't
there — the scan can't even see it.

36
04:53.000 --> 05:03.000
Turn history back on, same facts,
and they suddenly mean something.

37
05:03.000 --> 05:13.000
New, still open, verified fixed, regressed,
not retested, inconclusive.

38
05:13.000 --> 05:22.000
"Verified fixed" only counts if we reran
the same check and it came back clean.

39
05:22.000 --> 05:30.000
Not seeing a bug isn't the bug being gone.
Only memory knows a fix came back.

40
05:30.000 --> 05:38.000
The unglamorous stuff that just has to work.

41
05:38.000 --> 05:47.000
Same event twice — no-op.
A conflicting one — rejected.

42
05:47.000 --> 05:56.000
A report before the data's complete — blocked.
Shuffle the order — same report.

43
05:56.000 --> 06:03.000
Kill a transaction halfway — nothing left behind.

44
06:03.000 --> 06:10.000
Same facts, same answer, every time.
That's what you trust first.

45
06:10.000 --> 06:19.000
So why did I build this?
Honestly, mostly for fun.

46
06:19.000 --> 06:29.000
Armadin's probably already on this — but I think
there's real power in memory for security.

47
06:29.000 --> 06:39.000
Integration: I found T3MP3ST, a multi-agent
offensive framework — recon to exploit to report.

48
06:39.000 --> 06:47.000
Really cool, but no memory. Bolting Mahoraga
onto it would be a natural fit.

49
06:47.000 --> 06:57.000
Architecture: split the flow — a writer, a reader,
a report job — so each scales on its own.

50
06:57.000 --> 07:07.000
Plus environment drift, tradecraft memory,
hash-chained provenance, cross-customer learning.

51
07:07.000 --> 07:15.000
Each is its own project. But the core —
the memory engine — that's what's proven here.

52
07:15.000 --> 07:24.000
Everything you saw — the 3-to-1, identity, the six
categories, the correctness checks —

53
07:24.000 --> 07:31.000
none of it is hardcoded. Computed from the
actual run, identical every time.

54
07:31.000 --> 07:35.000
Fake data, yeah. But a real result.
Thanks for watching.
